<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1441,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1441,1467]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Alekseev &amp; Pankowski, 2020" authorityName="Alekseev &amp; Pankowski" authorityYear="2020" box="[283,398,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Madelinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,398,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Madelinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[408,516,1441,1467]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[408,516,1441,1467]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[534,643,1441,1467]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–2" captionStart-1="FIGURE 3" captionStartId-0="3.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,181,1884]" captionTargetBox-1="[297,1291,181,1909]" captionTargetId-0="figure-19@3.[151,1436,181,1884]" captionTargetId-1="figure-27@4.[291,1297,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–2. Madelinia gedanoposita gen. et sp. nov., holotype, No MAIG 6692, habitus: 1) dorsal view; 2) right lateral view. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm." captionText-1="FIGURE 3. Reconstruction of Madelinia gedanoposita gen. et sp. nov. from Baltic amber: habitus, dorsal view. Body length approximately 5.8 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418607" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418609" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4418607/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4418609/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Figs. 1–3</figureCitation>
) is assigned to the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1875" box="[934,1034,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hypulini">Hypulini</taxonomicName>
within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1125,1281,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Melandryinae">Melandryinae</taxonomicName>
based on the following combination of characters: (1) procoxae contiguous; (2) claws simple; (3) antennae 11-segmented; (4) base of pronotum closely associated with the base of elytra (not loosely laying over it as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pollock" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[1180,1324,1513,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Melandryini">Melandryini</taxonomicName>
); (5) head well visible from above (not vertically oriented as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1829" box="[770,914,1549,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Serropalpini">Serropalpini</taxonomicName>
); (6) elytra elongated, narrowly ovate; elytral punctation irregular and elytral vestiture depressed (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nikitsky" authorityYear="2007" box="[894,985,1585,1612]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Zilorini">Zilorini</taxonomicName>
); (7) lateral edges of pronotum not fully margined; (8) metatibia comparatively long (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName box="[809,931,1621,1648]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Orchesiini">Orchesiini</taxonomicName>
); (9) metatibial spurs comparatively short (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName box="[276,393,1657,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Orchesiini">Orchesiini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1829" box="[447,591,1657,1684]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Serropalpini">Serropalpini</taxonomicName>
); (10) penultimate tarsomere of all legs lobed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1441,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">
The new genus can be distinguished from all other described extant 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seidlitz" authorityYear="1875" box="[974,1074,1693,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hypulini">Hypulini</taxonomicName>
of the Northern Hemisphere by the following set of characters: (1) hind wings present, macropterous (in contrast to the wingless genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1856" box="[1345,1436,1729,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Marolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1345,1436,1729,1755]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Marolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyatake" authorityYear="1982" box="[199,383,1765,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Nipponomarolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,383,1765,1791]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Nipponomarolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (2) scutellum visible (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyatake" authorityYear="1982" box="[812,996,1765,1791]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Nipponomarolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[812,996,1765,1791]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Nipponomarolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (3) pronotal base distinctly margined (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paykull" authorityYear="1798" box="[313,406,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Hypulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[313,406,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Hypulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (4) pronotum with distinct basal triangular depressions (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1856" box="[1209,1300,1801,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Marolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1209,1300,1801,1827]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Marolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampe" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Neogonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Neogonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (5) pronotal base slightly narrower than elytral base (in contrast to distinctly narrower pronotal base in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyatake" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Nipponomarolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Nipponomarolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampe" authorityYear="1873" box="[352,464,1874,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Neogonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,464,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Neogonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (6) pronotum laterally margined at one third of posterior angles only (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1856" box="[151,242,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Marolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,242,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Marolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (7) elytra uniformly dark colored (in contrast to the elytra with color pattern in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paykull" authorityYear="1798" box="[1143,1236,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Hypulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1143,1236,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Hypulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1856" box="[1289,1380,1909,1935]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Marolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1289,1380,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Marolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); (8) metatarsomere 1 not shorter than one half of metatibia (in contrast to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hampe" authorityYear="1873" box="[929,1041,1946,1971]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Neogonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[929,1041,1946,1971]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Neogonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1441,2008]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="283" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName authority="Alekseev &amp; Pankowski, 2020" authorityName="Alekseev &amp; Pankowski" authorityYear="2020" box="[199,314,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Madelinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,314,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Madelinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[323,430,1981,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[323,430,1981,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
strongly resembles the European 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1856" box="[820,911,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Marolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[820,911,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Marolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Holarctic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paykull" authorityYear="1798" box="[1125,1218,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Hypulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1125,1218,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="282">Hypulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but does not fully correspond to either extant genus, and therefore is placed into a new genus within the tribe. This new genus from Baltic amber can be easily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[734,890,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Melandryinae">Melandryinae</taxonomicName>
described from Baltic amber using the combination of the abovementioned “tribal” characters 1, 4, 5, 7–9, as well the “generic” characters 3–6.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,259,285]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Note.</emphasis>
Due to the “milky” opacity in the amber obscuring part of the specimen, the sutures of the head, the proand mesothorax, the precise length of the epipleura, the form of distal labial palpomere, detail of the mouthparts, and the form of the eye margins (incised anteriorly or not) were impossible to examine. Also, the genitalia remained internal and were not studied in the specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="283" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new genus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alekseev &amp; Pankowski" authorityYear="2020" box="[679,794,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Melandryidae" genus="Madelinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[679,794,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Madelinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is of feminine gender. It is named after Madeline Pankowski (Rockville, 
<collectingRegion box="[372,484,439,465]" country="United States of America" name="Maryland" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Maryland</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[495,555,439,465]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">USA</collectingCountry>
), sister of the second author, who donated this amber inclusion to the Museum of Amber Inclusions for further scientific study and preservation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="283" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new genus is monotypic, represented by the 
<typeStatus box="[859,907,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
species only. Therefore, the generic description considerably overlaps that of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
